        <name>35.4.4.7 Conditional outcomes in a coin toss</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h4 class="HELM_exercise"&gt; Exercise &lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt; Two coins are tossed. Find the conditional probability that two Heads will occur given that at
least one occurs. I.e. let \(A = \{\text{at least one Head occurs}\}\), and \(B = \{\text{two Heads occur}\}\) and calculate \(\mathbb{P}(B|A)\). Give the probability as a fraction, not a decimal:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \(\mathbb{P}(B|A)=\quad\)[[input:ans1]][[validation:ans1]] &lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt; Solution &lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt; There are four possible outcomes from the coin tosses;&lt;/p&gt; 
\[TT, \, TH, \, HT \, \text{and} \, HH.\] 
&lt;p&gt;If it is given that there is at least one Head, i.e. \(A\) is true, then we know that there is three possible outcomes;&lt;/p&gt;
\[TH, \, HT \, \text{and} \, HH.\]
&lt;p&gt;Of these three, only one has two Heads, \(HH\), therefore the probability that there is two Heads given that there is at least one Head is \(1/3\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;More precisely, \(\mathbb{P}(B|A) = {@ta@}\).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;You can also reach this result by applying the formula\[\mathbb{P}(B|A)
    = \frac{\mathbb{P}(A|B)\mathbb{P}(B)}{\mathbb{P}(A)}\]which is a version of Bayes' theorem.&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
